tool.name: ConvertRasterToIWFMInput

param.name: inWorkspace
param.dialogReference: This is the folder directory or geodatabase that contains the raster data. The code will search through the directory specified and any subdirectories that may exist.

param.name: inRasters
param.dialogReference:
The options for this tool are populated depending on the folder, text file, or geodatabase specified in the first user input. If a parent directory is specified, any folders within the parent directory will also be searched and this part will return any raster datasets recognized by ESRI software.

This field allow for multiple selections. Check any combination of the raster datasets for processing.

Notes:

1. the tool is not currently set up to search through subfolders within the folders of the location specified. For example, if folder "Test" is provided as the main input workspace, all folders within "Test" will be searched for Raster datasets. However, any folders within those folders will not be searched.

2. It is important for processing that the name of the raster in some way specify the date in 'YYYYMM', 'YYYYM', 'YYYY_MM', or 'YYYY_M' format.

3. Consistent datums should be for all rasters used at a time.

4. Consistent units for the value field in the raster should also be used.

param.name: writeToFile
param.displayname: Write List of Rasters to File
param.dialogReference:
This allows the user to write the full path and name of all raster datasets to a text file. This can be used to edit and import back into the tool to use for processing.

checked - a file will be generated with all of the rasters checked from the rasters generated in the previous part of the tool.

unchecked (default) - no file will be generated

The file format allows for comments to be ignored that start with a '#'. All non-'#' lines should only contain the path and name for the rasters included.

For example, 'C:\Temp\raster.tif'

Note: If the user selected a text file in the first input, this option is disabled.

param.name: rasterTextFile
param.displayname: Name of Text File to Write Raster List
param.dialogReference:
This is the name of the file written to the output workspace with the raster paths and names stored in it.

Note: This field is only enabled if the 'Write List of Rasters to File' box is checked.

Provide a name and file extension. A default name is provided.

param.name: writeToFileOnly
param.dialogReference:
This check box allows the user to select whether or not the processing of the raster data will occur.

checked - only the rasters will be written to a text file of the name provided in the previous input.

unchecked (default) - all steps of processing will be performed by the tool.

Note: This parameter is only enabled if the 'Write List of Rasters to File' is checked.

param.name: inUnits
param.displayname: Select the Units for the Raster Datasets
param.dialogReference:
This is the field where the user specifies the native units of the value field for the raster datasets. This is a drop down menu with several different common units available.

The options are feet, inches, meters, millimeters

param.name: outUnits
param.displayname: Select the Units for the Output File Name
param.dialogReference:
This is the field where the user specifies the desired output units of the processed data. The program uses this information to determine a conversion factor between the native raster units and the desired output units.

This is a drop down menu with several different options available

The options are feet, inches, meters, and millimeters

param.name: aoiFeature
param.displayname: Select Polygon Feature Class For Area of Interest
param.dialogReference:
This is a feature class (shapefile format or geodatabase format) that represents the area of interest. Since this tool was designed for processing data for IWFM precipitation data, this would represent a merged feature class of the model elements and the small watersheds.

Notes:

1. This field is only optional if the write to file only check box is checked.

2. The merged dataset will need to be created prior to running this tool. The merge tool is part of the standard ArcToolbox.

3. it is ideal if the spatial reference (i.e. coordinate system and projection) are the same. Otherwise, differences may be significant in some cases.

param.name: aoiIDField
param.displayname: Select ID Field from Feature Class
param.dialogReference:
This is a list of the fields from the attribute table of the feature class specified for the area of interest. The field selected here should represent a unique ID for each element and small watershed.

For example, if there are N elements and M small watersheds, then the selected ID field should have a number starting with 1 to N representing elements 1 to N and N+1 to N+M representing small watersheds 1 to M.

Note: This field is only optional if the write to file check box is checked.

param.name: outWorkspace
param.dialogReference:
This is the output folder or file directory. The user can navigate to any location on the harddrive or network as well as create a new folder to save the outputs.

Note:

1. This will allow a geodatabase to be specified. However, the tool is not set up to allow for this because the final output generated in this location is a text file.

2. Intermediate steps will be saved to folders within this location.

param.name: outFileName
param.dialogReference: This is the name of the IWFM input text file that is generated by the tool. The user needs to type this into the field.

tool.summary: This tool is designed to assign gridded raster data to the IWFM model grid and input file format. It is currently set up for processing the input file for precipitation. It was designed for the purpose of converting PRISM raster data to the IWFM input file format for the fine grid version of the California Central Valley Groundwater Surface-Water Simulation Model (C2VSimFG). However, intermediate processing steps may make this tool useful for other purposes.
tool.usage: This tool is provided free for anyone to use. However, it required a license to ArcGIS for Desktop or ArcGIS Pro. It has undergone limited testing on both platforms, but is to be used at the users own risk.
